Kansas lets friends share a virtual deck of cards across their phones.

The goal is to enable users to use their smartphone, tablet, or laptop
in place of any set of cards. Like in games using physical cards,
Kansas is designed under the assumption that players trust each other
and can negotiate rules and movements in person.

Kansas was originally built for Python 2-era tooling and has now been
updated to run on modern Python 3 environments.

Features:

    real-time synchronization
    cross-platform support

Dependencies (use ./install_deps.sh):

    python3
    websockets
    pillow (optional, used for image resizing)

Running a test server:

    Starting the web server and websocket server:

        $ ./start

    Then, visit:

        http://localhost:8000/index.html#playerName


MTG card search now uses the Scryfall API for card metadata and image URLs.
